<DIV class=3Dpadding10>
<H1>Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP)</H1>
<H2 class=3Dtop><A id=3D01 name=3D01></A>What is the purpose of the =
CMVP?</H2>
<P>On July 17, 1995, the National Institute of Standards and Technology =
(NIST)=20
established the Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) that =
validates=20
cryptographic modules to Federal Information Processing Standards=20
(FIPS)<NOBR>140-1</NOBR> Security Requirements for Cryptographic =
Modules, and=20
other FIPS cryptography based standards. The CMVP is a joint effort =
between NIST=20
and the Communications Security Establishment Canada (CSEC). FIPS 140-2, =

Security Requirements for Cryptographic Modules, was released on May 25, =
2001=20
and supersedes FIPS 140-1. </P>
<P>Modules validated as conforming to FIPS 140-1 and FIPS 140-2 are =
accepted by=20
the Federal Agencies of both countries for the protection of sensitive=20
information.</P>
<P>Vendors of cryptographic modules use independent, accredited =
Cryptographic=20
and Security Testing (CST) laboratories to test their modules. The CST=20
laboratories use the Derived Test Requirements (DTR), Implementation =
Guidance=20
(IG) and applicable CMVP programmatic guidance to test cryptographic =
modules=20
against the applicable standards.. NIST's Computer Security Division =
(CSD) and=20
CSEC jointly serve as the Validation Authorities for the program, =
validating the=20
test results and issuing certificates.</P><A class=3DtopLink=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cmvp/index.html#top">Back to =
Top</A>=20
<H2><A id=3D02 name=3D02></A>What is the applicability of CMVP to the US =

government?</H2>
<P>FIPS 140-1 became a mandatory standard for the protection of =
sensitive data=20
when the Secretary of Commerce signed the standard on January 11, 1994. =
FIPS=20
140-2 supersedes FIPS 140-1 and the standard was signed on May 25, 2001. =
The=20
applicability statement from FIPS 140-2 (page iv):</P>
<P><B>7. Applicability.</B> This standard is applicable to all Federal =
agencies=20
that use cryptographic-based security systems to protect sensitive =
information=20
in computer and telecommunication systems (including voice systems) as =
defined=20
in Section 5131 of the Information Technology Management Reform Act of =
1996,=20
Public Law 104-106. This standard shall be used in designing and =
implementing=20
cryptographic modules that Federal departments and agencies operate or =
are=20
operated for them under contract. Cryptographic modules that have been =
approved=20
for classified use may be used in lieu of modules that have been =
validated=20
against this standard. The adoption and use of this standard is =
available to=20
private and commercial organizations.</P><A class=3DtopLink=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cmvp/index.html#top">Back to =
Top</A>=20
<H2><A id=3D03 name=3D03></A>Use of Unvalidated Cryptographic Modules by =
Federal=20
Agencies and Departments</H2>
<P>FIPS 140-2 precludes the use of unvalidated cryptography <STRONG>for =
the=20
cryptographic protection</STRONG> of sensitive or valuable data within =
Federal=20
systems. Unvalidated cryptography is viewed by NIST as providing =
<STRONG>no=20
protection</STRONG> to the information or data - in effect the data =
would be=20
considered unprotected plaintext. <STRONG>If the agency specifies that =
the=20
information or data be cryptographically protected</STRONG>, then FIPS =
140-2 is=20
applicable. In essence, if cryptography is required, then it must be=20
validated.</P>
<P>With the passage of the Federal Information Security Management Act =
(FISMA)=20
of 2002, there is no longer a statutory provision to allow for agencies =
to waive=20
mandatory Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS). The waiver =
provision=20
had been included in the Computer Security Act of 1987; however, FISMA=20
supersedes that Act. Therefore, the references to the "waiver process" =
contained=20
in many of the FIPS listed below are no longer operative.</P>
<P>As background, below is a list of facts found in FIPS 140-2 and other =

supporting NIST documents:</P>
<UL class=3Dbullets1>
  <LI>Cryptography: The discipline which embodies principles, means and =
methods=20
  for the transformation of data to hide its information content, =
prevent its=20
  undetected modification, prevent its unauthorized use or a combination =

  thereof. [ANSI X9.31]<BR>Cryptography deals with the transformation of =

  ordinary text (plaintext) into coded form (ciphertext) by encryption =
and=20
  transformation of ciphertext into plaintext by decryption. [NIST SP=20
800-2]</LI>
  <LI>The selective application of technological and related procedural=20
  safeguards is an important responsibility of every Federal =
organization in=20
  providing adequate security in its computer and telecommunication =
systems.=20
  This standard [FIPS 140-2] provides a standard that will be used by =
Federal=20
  organizations when these organizations specify that =
cryptographic-based=20
  security systems are to be used to provide protection for sensitive or =

  valuable data. [FIPS 140-2]</LI>
  <LI>The FIPS 140-2 standard is applicable to all Federal agencies that =
use=20
  cryptographic-based security systems to protect sensitive information =
in=20
  computer and telecommunication systems (including voice systems) as =
defined in=20
  Section 5131 of the Information Technology Management Reform Act of =
1996,=20
  Public Law 104-106. [FIPS 140-2]</LI>
  <LI>FIPS 140-2 shall be used in designing and implementing =
cryptographic=20
  modules that Federal departments and agencies operate or are operated =
for them=20
  under contract. [FIPS 140-2]</LI>
  <LI>With the passage of the <A class=3Dpdf=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/drivers/documents/FISMA-final.pdf"=20
  target=3D_blank>Federal Information Security Management Act of =
2002</A>, there=20
  is no longer a statutory provision to allow for agencies to waive =
mandatory=20
  Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS). The waiver provision =
had been=20
  included in the Computer Security Act of 1987; however, FISMA =
supersedes that=20
  Act. Therefore, the references to the "waiver process" contained in =
many of=20
  the FIPS are no longer operative. For further information, please go =
to the=20
  CMVP <A title=3DFAQs=20
  href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cmvp/faqs.html">FAQs</A> =
Section=20
  3.2.<BR></LI></UL><A class=3DtopLink=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cmvp/index.html#top">Back to =
Top</A>=20
<H2><A id=3D04 name=3D04></A>What is the status of modules validated to =
FIPS=20
<NOBR>140-1?</NOBR></H2>
<P>FIPS 140-1 became a mandatory standard for the protection of =
sensitive data=20
when the Secretary of Commerce signed the standard on January 11, 1994. =
FIPS=20
140-2 supersedes FIPS 140-1 and the standard was signed on May 25, 2001. =
The=20
Implementation Schedule statement from FIPS 140-2 (page v):=20
<P><B>14. Implementation Schedule</B>. This standard (FIPS 140-2) =
becomes=20
effective six months after approval by the Secretary of Commerce. A =
transition=20
period from November 25, 2001 until six months after the effective date =
is=20
provided to enable all agencies to develop plans for the acquisition of =
products=20
that are compliant with FIPS 140-2. Agencies may retain and use FIPS =
140-1=20
validated products that have been purchased before the end of the =
transition=20
period. After the transition period, modules will no longer be tested =
against=20
the FIPS 140-1 requirements. After the transition period, all previous=20
validations against FIPS 140-1 will still be recognized.=20
<P>The CMVP posted a clarification to the implementation schedule on =
February=20
04, 2002 which was posted in the CMVP FAQ Section 1 Overview: </P>
<P>FIPS 140-2, Security Requirements for Cryptographic Modules, was =
released on=20
May 25, 2001 and supersedes FIPS 140-1. However, agencies may continue =
to=20
purchase, retain and use FIPS 140-1 validated modules after May 25, =
2002.=20
Modules validated as conforming to FIPS 140-1 and FIPS 140-2 are =
accepted by the=20
Federal Agencies of both countries for the protection of sensitive =
information.=20
<U>However, a federal agency may choose to only procure a FIPS 140-2 =
validated=20
module.</U> </P>
<P><A class=3DtopLink=20
href=3D"http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/STM/cmvp/index.html#top">Back to =
Top</A> </P>
<H2><A id=3D05 name=3D05></A>How does Common Criteria (CC) relate to =
FIPS=20
<NOBR>140-2?</NOBR></H2>
<P>If the operational environment is a modifiable operational =
environment, the=20
operating system requirements of the Common Criteria are applicable at =
Security=20
Levels 2 and above.</P>
<P>FIPS 140-1 required evaluated operating systems that referenced the =
Trusted=20
Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC) classes C2, B1 and B2. =
However,=20
TCSEC is no longer in use and has been replaced by the Common Criteria.=20
Consequently, FIPS 140-2 now references the Common Criteria for =
Information=20
Technology Security Evaluation (CC), ISO/IEC 15408:1999.</P>
<P>The Common Criteria (CC) and FIPS 140-2 are different in the =
abstractness and=20
focus of tests. FIPS 140-2 testing is against a defined cryptographic =
module and=20
provides a suite of conformance tests to four security levels. FIPS =
140-2=20
describes the requirements for cryptographic modules and includes such =
areas as=20
physical security, key management, self tests, roles and services, etc. =
The=20
standard was initially developed in 1994 - prior to the development of =
the CC.=20
CC is an evaluation against a created protection profile (PP) or =
security target=20
(ST). Typically, a PP covers a broad range of products.</P>
<P>A CC evaluation does not supersede or replace a validation to either =
FIPS=20
140-1 or FIPS 140-2. The four security levels in FIPS 140-1 and FIPS =
140-2 do=20
not map directly to specific CC EALs or to CC functional requirements. A =
CC=20
certificate cannot be a substitute for a FIPS 140-1 or FIPS 140-2=20
certificate.<BR></P>
